             Cantaloupe



Loading the Game

     Turn on your Amiga, wait for the "Insert Disk" prompt, and insert the
Cantaloupe disk.  When Workbench appears, double click on the disk icon,
and then double click on the Cantaloupe game icon.  The game will load in
a few seconds.


Installing the Game to Hard Disk

     Open the drawer of your hard disk that you want to install the game
into.  Insert the Cantaloupe disk, and wait for it's icon to appear.  Drag
the icon into the hard disk drawer you have opened.  Now load the game by
opening the newly created drawer, and double clicking on the game icon.


Starting the Game

     When the game has loaded, you will be presented with the title screen
sequence.  Press fire to bring up the Options screen.  Move the yellow bar
(using the joystick) to highlight an option, and press fire to activate
the option.  For the moment, highlight "Start the Game", and press fire. 
The game sequence will now begin, and you will be presented with the Get
Ready screen.  Press fire to start the level.


Aim of the Game

     In the game, you play the part of a red sphere whose sole reason for
being is to rid screens of tiles from the evil yellow/orange and pink
stripey tiles.  You move the sphere by using the joystick (push up to move
it up one tile, right to go right a tile, and so on), and destroy the
yellow/orange and pink stripey tiles by moving over them.

     However, there are other types of tile that can be moved over, to
either help or hinder your progress through a level.  It is probably best
to experiment with the different types, but here is a summary for
reference:

1.  Normal tiles:  These rather fetchingly chequered tiles can be moved
over freely without any ill effects.

2.  The yellow/orange stripey tiles:  These all have to be destroyed.  To
destroy a tile, simply move onto it, and then move off it.  The tile will
then disappear.  There is, however, quite a strict time limit on the
amount of time you may spend on one of these tiles before moving off it:
if you exceed this limit, the tile will be destroyed anyway, along with
your sphere.  You will then lose a life, and have to restart the level.

3. The pink stripey tiles:  When these are moved over, they will turn into
the yellow/orange stripey tiles, and will be treated as such from then on.
 However, you may move onto one, wait until you hear a bell sound
(whereupon the pink tile will have changed to a yellow/orange tile), and
then move off it.  As it has all ready been changed to a yellow/orange
tile, it will disappear as you move off it.

4. Ice:  Move onto one of these, and you will slide across it, moving in
the same direction as you were going when you moved onto it.  You have no
control over your movement when you are moving over these.

5. Horizontal/Vertical movement only tiles:  The horizontal movement only
tile will, surprisingly enough, only let you move horizontally, i.e. you
can only move on to and off of them using the left and right hand sides of
the tile.  Vertical movement only tiles are similar, but only allow
vertical movement.

6. Arrows:  Move onto one of these, and you will be moved, conveyor-belt
style, in the direction of the arrow.  For example, move onto an up-arrow
from any direction and you will henceforth proceed in a northerly
direction, whether you want to or not.

7. Teleport:  You can treat these as normal tiles if you just want to move
over them.  However, move over one and press fire, and you will disappear
only to reappear at another predetermined point on the level.

8. Switches:  Again, for moving-over-the-tile purposes, treat these as
normal tiles.  But pressing fire over one of them will toggle one or two
other "switchable" tiles on the level.  Switchable tiles have either a
tick or a cross on, and are either non-fatal or fatal to move over
respectively.  A tick will change to a cross, and a cross to a tick.

9. Exit:  When you have destroyed all of the yellow/orange and pink
stripey tiles, you may be at a bit of a loose end.  To now move to the
next level in the game, you must reach an Exit tile.  When you move over
this, you will disappear, and the level will be complete.  Exit tiles are
only functional once you have destroyed all the destructible (i.e.
yellow/orange and pink stripey) tiles on the level: before this point,
just treat them as normal tiles.

     It is recommended that you spend a few games just playing around with
the tiles, to see what each does, how they react in  different
circumstances, and so on.


How to Die

     Dying is easy to achieve, and sometimes necessary to do deliberately
(e.g. if the level has become impossible to complete).  There are four
main methods:
- Moving off a tile into a space where there is no tile.  You will fall
into the unrealistic water below and perish.
- Staying still too long on a yellow/orange stripey tile will cause you to
expire.
- Moving onto a fatal, changeable, crossed tile will be the cause of
shuffling off your mortal coil.
- Press either of the keys "D" or "Q" (D to die and restart the level, Q
to quit the current game and return to the title screen).  This will
result in you becoming an ex-sphere.  Sometimes pressing a key is the only
way to exit certain levels, as you may become trapped in a certain
combination of tiles (e.g. a down arrow above an up arrow: you will
continually move between the two tiles without being able to die).


Other Options Explained

     Here the other options in the options menu will be explained:
- Enter Password:  Allows you to enter a password using the keyboard. 
Only the current game's stages will be searched for the password you have
entered.
- Choose Game Number:  A game is simply a set of stages.  A stage is a set
of five levels.  You can choose which game you want to play (out of a
possible 1000) using this option: you may select which stage you want to
play in a game by entering a password (explained above).  Choose the game
number by using the arrows above and below each number.  To jump to the
next game number which has some stages in by using the "Next" button (to
search backwards, press the "Prev" button).  The number of stages in a the
game number selected will be displayed in the corner of the screen.  Press
"OK" to select that game number as the one you want to play.
- Read Instructions:  This will simply display a these instructions in a
more brief form.  Press fire to advance a page.
- Load and Save High Scores: Allows you to load and save the high score
table.  It will load or save it according to the currently selected game
number.  This means you could have up to 1000 different high score tables
stored on disk, keeping a high score table for each game.
- Exit:  Go back to the title screen (useful to see a newly loaded high
score table).


Entering a New High Score

     If you score highly enough, you may qualify for a high score.  Use
the mouse or joystick to highlight and select (press fire or mouse button)
whichever letters make up your name.  You can also use the keyboard to
type in your name.  Your name will be displayed at the bottom of the
screen as it is being entered.  When using the mouse or joystick, use the
characters <Del> to delete your last letter entry, <Spc> to add a space,
and <End> to finish entering your name (on keyboard, use the backspace
key, the space bar, and the return key to achieve the same effect).


