            Level Editor



How to Load

     To load up the level editor, simply turn on (or re-boot) your Amiga
and insert the disk with the level editor on.  The disk should boot, and
the Workbench screen should soon appear.  Double click on the disk icon,
and then double click on the "LevelEditor" icon in the window that has
just appeared.  The program will now load up and initialise.


Installing onto Hard Disk

     Assuming that you have all ready installed the game (see game user
guide), firstly boot your Amiga from your hard disk, and then open the
drawer the game is in.  Insert the disk with the level editor on, and
double click on the disk icon.  Now simply drag the "LevelEditor" icon
across from the floppy disk to the hard disk drawer you have opened.

     To run it form hard disk, simply boot from hard disk, open the drawer
the game and level editor are in, and double click on the "LevelEditor"
icon.


Loading and Saving Stages

     Stages are blocks of five levels (or screens of tiles).  A "game" is
a group of stages (any number from 0 to 100 stages can be in a particular
game.  There can be up to 1000 different games stored).

     If you know which stage you want to load, and know which game it is
in, the quickest way is to type in the game and stage numbers in the
particular boxes on the main menu.  To do this, click on the box with the
mouse, and type in the number using standard Amiga editing facilities
(e.g. backspace, delete, cursor keys,etc.).  Once you have entered this,
click on the "Load Stage" button.  Similarly, to save a stage in memory to
disk, type in the stage and game numbers you want it saved as, and click
on the "Save Stage" button.

     However, most of the time you will not be sure of the numbers, and
whether they actually exist or not.  In these cases, click on the "Choose
Stage" button on the main menu, and a new screen will open.


Choose Stage

     The main function of this screen is to select which numbers will go
into the game and stage boxes on the main menu.  There are two main lists
on this screen: a list of the games that exist, and a list of stages that
exist in the selected game.  Select a game by clicking on it's number in
the game list: the stage list should update immediately.  Select the stage
you want by clicking on the number in the stage list.  The numbers in the
Game and Stage boxes should update automatically.  Clicking on "OK" now
will return you to the main menu with the relevant numbers transferred
from this screen.  However, there are other functions the screen can
perform.

     The stage list is a list of the stage numbers that exist in the game,
along with the passwords for each of them.  Usually, the passwords can
help to identify which stage is which.  You can edit the passwords for an
entire game without having to load each stage in by:
- Selecting a game from the list
- Select a stage from the list
- Edit the password in the password box
- When all passwords have been edited (as shown in the list), click on the
"Save Passwords" button.

     The "Auto-save passwords?" tick box represents whether the password
list will be automatically be saved whenever the game number is changed. 
If it isn't ticked, a requester will be opened each time you change games
(and you've altered the password list) asking if you want to save it.

     There is a bank of buttons along the bottom of screen.  Here the
following functions can be accessed:

"Create Stage":  Will create a blank stage, of the number you have entered
in the stage box.  To create a new game, simply enter the new game number
in the game box, and press Enter.  It will be created automatically.

"Delete Stage" & "Delete Game":  These will delete the selected stage or
game.  Be careful, these functions are non-reversible, and data will be
lost forever.

"Compress Game":  Will renumber all of the stages in the game, preserving
their order, starting from 0 and increasing in steps of one.

"Validate Game":  This will validate all the files for the current game
number.  It will make sure they are all present, and in some cases check
that they contain the correct information (some files cannot be checked
like this).  It will create any missing files.

"Validate All":  Basically performs the same operation as "Validate Game"
for all the games that exist, and also check extra files that concern the
entire list of games.

"Load Stage" & "Save Stage":  These perform the same operations as they do
on the main menu (i.e. load the selected stage into memory, or save the
stage in memory to the selected stage number).

"OK" & "Cancel":  These both return you to the main menu.  OK will return
the new values for the Game and Stage to the main menu:  Cancel will
simply return you to the main menu, replacing the new values of Game and
Stage with what they were before you called up the screen.


Selecting the level

     To select which level you wish to edit, on the main menu, simply
click on the box next to the appropriate number.  You can edit the time
limit for the selected level in the same way as you did for the game and
stage numbers.  The time limit will be in seconds, and automatically
stored once entered.




Check for Errors

     Clicking on the "Check for Errors" button  will quickly look through
all the levels in memory to check for any basic errors that can be picked
up.  The errors found will be presented in a list form underneath the
button.  The errors it will find would be ones such as whether each level
had a comment, an Exit tile, any destructible tiles, unconnected switches
and teleports, and whether the start position is safe or not.  It cannot
detect whether a level is can be completed or not.

     The errors will contain the level number it refers to, and
coordinates where applicable.  For example:

     1: Unconnected switch (12,5)

     This means that there is an unconnected switch at coordinates (12,5)
on the first level.


Edit Comment

     Clicking on this button on the main menu will allow you to enter a
comment for the selected level.  It will be displayed on the "Get Ready"
screen before the level.


Test Level

     The "Test Level" option allows you to try out the selected level
(useful for testing whether a level can be completed or not).  It will
simulate the game as if the selected level has just been reached.  For
details of how to play the game, please refer to the game user guide.

     When the level has been either completed or the player has died, a
screen will appear informing you of how long was spent playing the level. 
This can be very useful to decide what time limit to set a for a level.


Edit Level

     This main menu option allows you to actually edit the selected
level's map.  The map display shows how the level looks at present.  To
alter the level map:
- Select a tile type by clicking on the row of tiles at the bottom of the
screen (you can also use the cursor keys for this).  The selected tile
type should now have an arrow above it.
- Move your mouse into the map area.  The tile follows your mouse over
this display.  Decide where you would like to place the tile, move the
mouse there and press the left mouse button.

     Click on the left and right arrows next to the level number to move
up or down a level.  The map display will update automatically.  Use this
as a short-cut so you don't have to go back to the main menu just to
change the level number.

     When you click on the "Clear" button, the current level will be
cleared of tiles.  This operation is irreversible.  Click on "Exit" to go
back to the main menu.

     There are also four other options available at the bottom of the
screen, and all work in more or less the same way.  The icons mean, from
left to right:
- Connect teleport with destination tile
- Link switch with one changeable tile
- Link switch with two changeable tiles
- Choose start position

     For the first three, after pressing the icon, you should then click
on a teleport or switch (whatever it says on the message line at the top
of the screen).  You will then be asked to click on another tile (either
the destination or changeable tile(s)).  If you have previously set the
tiles, you may see where they are by pressing the right mouse button at
this point.  A message ("To:") will appear over the default tile.  You may
choose any legal tile by moving your mouse over it and pressing the left
mouse button.

     To choose the start position, simply click on the icon and then the
tile position you want the player to start at.  Again, to view the current
start position, click on the icon, then move your mouse over the map and
press the right mouse button.

     To abort any of these operations, move your mouse off the map and
press the left mouse button.  At any time, you may look at the message
line which will tell you what you should be doing.


Quitting the Program

     Get to the main menu, and click on the "Quit Program" button.  You
will be asked to confirm your choice, and if you do the program will end
and leave you with a Workbench screen.  Please remember to save your work
before you do this, as if you don't it will be lost forever.


